January 1521":"januari 1521","after 1444":"na 1444","Keele, Staffordshire, , England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Keele, Staffordshire, England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Westminster, London, England":"Westminster, London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Sandbach, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1420–January 1521":"1420–January 1521","1420–1521":"1420–1521","1424–1483":"1424–1483","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1444–Female":"1444–Deceased","1373–1384":"1373–1384","1424":"1424","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","29 November 1483":"29 November 1483","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1483":"1483","January 1521":"January 1521","after 1444":"after 1444","Keele, Staffordshire, , England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Keele, Staffordshire, England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Westminster, London, England":"Westminster, London, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Sandbach, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Snede","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Sneyd in Burslem, The Sneyd near Bloxwich (both Staffordshire), or Snead Farm and Snead Common in Rock (Worcestershire), all derived from Middle English <i>snede</i> ‘detached piece of land or woodland’ (Old English <i>snǣd</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Sneath","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and Rutland): habitational name from Snaith (Yorkshire), from Old Norse <i>sneith</i> ‘slice of land, piece of land cut off’. Compare   Sneed  ."]},{"name":"Snead","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Sneed  ."]},{"name":"Snee","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Sneed   with loss of the final consonant.","Irish (Mayo and Sligo): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Sniadhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sniadhach</i>’, a personal name apparently meaning ‘nitty’, from <i>sneadh</i> ‘nit’."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Snede was born in 1420, in Keele, Staffordshire, England as the son of William Sneyd. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Agnes Sutton. He died in January 1521, in Staffordshire, England, at the age of 101."},"et":{"1420–January 1521":"1420–jaanuar 1521","1420–1521":"1420–1521","1424–1483":"1424–1483","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1444–Female":"1444–Surnud","1373–1384":"1373–1384","1424":"1424","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","29 November 1483":"29. november 1483","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1483":"1483","January 1521":"jaanuar 1521","after 1444":"pärast 1444","Keele, Staffordshire, , England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Keele, Staffordshire, England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Westminster, London, England":"Westminster, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Sandbach, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1420–January 1521":"1420–tammikuu 1521","1420–1521":"1420–1521","1424–1483":"1424–1483","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1444–Female":"1444–Kuollut","1373–1384":"1373–1384","1424":"1424","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1521":"1521","29 November 1483":"29. marraskuuta 1483","1420":"1420","1475":"1475","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1483":"1483","January 1521":"tammikuu 1521","after 1444":"1444 jälkeen","Keele, Staffordshire, , England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Keele, Staffordshire, England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Westminster, London, England":"Westminster, London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, 